Wine Analysis by Mathias Wainer

This dataset is composed of 1599 observations of different red wines and 11 variables. The dataset was created by: Paulo Cortez (Univ. Minho), Antonio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida, Telmo Matos and Jose Reis. By making this data publicly available it allows everyone to explore and come up with original analysis. The output variable (y) is the quality of wine as determined by wine someliers. It is the hope of the creators and anyone who explores the data to come up with conclusions on what variables make the best wines.

We can see above x being all the observations, the 11 variables and quality as the output variable. We also can look at the summary statistics for each one. Quality was printed again since it should be our focus to decipher how it is shaped by every variable.

We can see that quality is clustred around scores 5 and 6 (80% of observations). Both fixed and volatile acidities follow what appears to be a normal distribution. Citric.acid does not follow a normal distribution and may even be bimodal.

We can see that residual.sugar and chlorides have some extreme right tailed values. Total.sulfur.dioxide has 2 values near the 300 range but is otherwise under 100 sulfates (g/dm^3)

These 4 grapgs appear to be quite normally distributed. Graphing sulphates by limiting the x axis around 1.25 (g/dm^3) may express the distribution more accurately.

After limiting the x axis for residual.sugar we can see the distribution be more normal and center around 2.25.

After limiting the x axis for chlorides we can see the distribution be more normal and center around 0.8 (g/dm^3).

These two line graphs show the normal distribution of density and the non- normal distribution of citric.acid.

Univariate Analysis

After creating charts for all the variables in the dataset I was pleasently surprised. Most of variable frequencies follow a pretty well defined normal distribution, examples are volatile.acidity and fixed.acidity.

The variables residual.sugar and chlorides and some other variables (to some extent) had some extreme right values. Once the x axis were limited to exclude extreme values the data became more normal.

Something to explore in the bivariate analysis section is the citric.acid variable. It does not appear to have a normal distribution.

Something to note is that over 81% the wine quality scores are either 5 or 6. To get better correlation statistics and figure out what variables affect it would be beneficial to have a wide range of quality scores.

First I graphed density vs alcohol which should be negatively correlated since alcohol is less dense than water. A spearson correlation test confirmed it. I did the same for free.sulfur and total.sulfur. Predictably total sulfur was positively correlated with free sulfur.

After graphing each variable against quality. I added some transparency for readibility and added a mean line (blue) and a linear regression line (red). After visual analysis i would like to run pearson correlation for only 4 of the variables that had large slopes on the red line (fitted line). The 4 largest slopes were for variables alcohol, sulphates, citric.acid and volatile.acidity.

Bivariate Analysis

First I ran two scatter plots of variables I expected would be correlated to a high degree (alcohol vs density, free.sulphates vs total.sulphates) to confirm my suspicion.

Next I ran each variable against quality and took note of highly-slopped means and smoothed lines. I identified citric acid, alcohol, volatile.acidity, and sulphates as possible candidates to have a large regression.

After computing the correlation if the 4 identified variables only citric acid had a correlation score between (-0.25,0.25) meaning the correlation was especially weak.

Alcohol had the largest presented correlation to quality which suggests the comical conclusion that a drunk wine tester is a happy wine tester. However future causal research must be performed to verify this.

Multivariate Plots Section

The graph volatile.acidity vs quality by alcohol buckets appears to have a trend in which the lower the acidity the better the quality. We can see an overwhelming number of blue and purple in the top right of the plot. purple

Citric.acid vs quality by alcohol buckets appears to have a positive trend. However it appears (at least visually) that alcohol content has a larger effect on quality than citric acid.

The sulphates vs quality by alcohol buckets has many 7 and 8 rated quality wines in the middle of the x range (around .75)

After visually inspecting all the graphs I attempted to fit quality to be dependent on citric.acid, sulphates, volatile.acidity and alcohol. The results had very poor confidence intervals. The best performing parameters was alchol, sulphates and volatile.acidity. Running that fitted model was much better as most variables had a 99.9% confidence interval.

I then pulled the quality score for observation 250, which was six and ran it against the model which predicted 5.52 (rounded up thats 6). Obervation 500 had a quality score of 6 and the fitted model predicted 5.86 which is pretty close.

Multivariate Analysis

After separating alcohol content into four buckets and running scatter plots on the other three identified variables several trends became apparent. Alcohol had the largest effect on quality of content. Very few highly rated wines were in the two lower alcohol groups. Additionally because of interaction between volatile.acids and citric.acid one of the two had to be dropped from the fitted model.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

I chose this graph because it illustrates the highest single factor correlation to a wines quality score. The wines with higher alcohol appear to on average to have higher scores. The red fitted line confirms our visual observation.

Plot Two

Description Two

This graph plots citric acid vs quality score. It is interesting that there are essentially no observations above the fitted line that have an alcohol content in the lower alcohol bucket. At the same time we can see that a high citric acid content may propel some wines in the lower alcohol category to 7 and 8 ratings.

Plot Three

Description Three

I chose the sulphates vs quality plot because it displays how values further from the fitted mean can accentuate its slope. There are many more wines with the two lower levels of alcohol content than the two higher ones. Additionaly the few high quality wines tend to have a higher alcohol content, either due to causation or due to sampling. This fact drives the fitted mean line to a more pronounced slope.

Reflection

During the initial single variable analysis I was pleasently surprised how normal all the distributions were. It makes sense that most variables would be normal since wines are produced in a similar fashion. The biggest struggle during the analysis was that the output variable quality was discrete and only had 5 possible outcomes (3 to 8 range). This fact makes graphing it more difficult as you dont want too much overlapping observations clustered around each quality score.

Future analysis of this dataset should focus on developing and testing various predictive models. These models can then be tested against new observations to test its efficacy. I read online that it is possible to randomly use only half a data set to create a model and then have it tested against the remaining half. It would be interesting to do this procedure and statistically evaluate it.
